feat(R65): PMOS module implemented -- v1 prototype collapse, fixed (L_div + diverse init + harder tau)

pmos_model.py (PMOSNet: shared APTD backbone + K prototype embeddings each modulating the
warp+residual head -> K candidate post-ops; init from APTD warpres step_2000) + train_pmos.py
(soft-min set loss + usage balance; eval best-of-K vs proto0).

v1 (pmos_K4, K=4, tau=0.05, no L_div, zero-init proto) COLLAPSED: best-of-K == proto0 every
step (SSIM 0.293->0.307, LPIPS 0.63->0.66), usage=[54,0,0,0], yet training qbar uniform
[.25,.25,.25,.25] -> the K prototypes degenerated to identical functions, best-of-K zero gain.
Classic multiple-choice-learning collapse. Cause: missing explicit diversity term (was in the
spec, I omitted it) + zero-init (start identical) + tau too soft. NOT a PMOS-infeasibility (R62
gate proved coverable discrete modes, oracle best-of-K EV 0.21-0.28).

Fix (v2 pmos_K4b): light L_div (pairwise output-L1 hinge, margin 0.06, lambda 0.3) + diverse
proto init (proto0=base, rest N(0,0.1)) + tau 0.05->0.02. Re-running 2500 steps. Gate: usage
spreads + best-of-K >> proto0 -> PMOS works; else image-level headroom too small -> lead with
APTD, report PMOS as honest weak/negative.
